post_text: An amazing career of service to our country by alumna and Rear Admiral Janet Russell Donovan!
shared_text:
Lakewood Rangers Education Foundation
Yesterday at 10:00 AM ¬∑

Hall of Fame recall for today: Janet Donovan '76. Janet was inducted into the LHS Distinguished Alumni Hall of Fame in 2013.

The daughter of two LHS alumni, Rear Admiral Janet Russell Donovan earned a Bachelor of Arts degree from the College of Wooster and a law degree from Case Western Reserve University School of Law. She has since led a long a illustrious career within the ranks of the U.S. Navy.

While on active duty, Donovan spent time serving as legal council to various naval boards and offices as well as taking on the role of judge on board active naval ships. Of particular note were the many staffs with which she conducted special work, including NATO Supreme Allied Commander‚Ä¶

Hall of Fame recall for today: JoAnne Van Burik Young '82. JoAnne was inducted into the LHS Distinguished Alumni Hall of Fame in 2001.

JoAnne is a physician, scientist, and Editor-in-Chief of Clinical Microbiology Reviews, published by the American Society for Microbiology. Her expertise is in the areas of transplantation, infectious diseases, infections of the immune compromised host, and clinical mycology and virology. She is Medical Director of the Adult Transplant Infectious Disease Program at the University of Minnesota. Hall of Fame recall for today: Mariann Becks. Inducted into the Lakewood Staff Hall of Fame in 2008.

Mariann Miller Becks was hired in 1964 to be the first swimming pool guard in the city of Lakewood. Nine years later, she was named to coordinate the entire swim instruction program for the Recreation Department by Lakewood Board of Education, post she held until 2002. In 1973, Mariann was named the L-Room Director which also gave her the responsibility of social director for the high school. Lakewood Rangers Education Foundation
September 1 at 10:00 AM ¬∑

Hall of Fame recall for today: David Louie, LHS 1968. Inducted into the LHS Distinguished Alumni Hall of Fame in 1995.

David Louie has been a reporter for ABC7 News for 50 years. He reports on technology and business around the San Francisco Bay Area. David Louie's involvement with reporting and communication technology started early with his involvement in the LHS Times.

David earned a Bachelor of Science in Journalism from Northwestern University in 1972. After graduating from Northwestern University's Medill School of Journalism in 1972, Louie was immediately hired by KGO-TV News, an affiliate of ABC in San Francisco, California. He was one of the first Asian American TV journalists‚Ä¶

post_text: We were pleased that the Governor announced today that Cuyahoga County is now at alert Level 2 or Orange in the Ohio Public Health Advisory System. This announcement is an indication that our county is getting healthier, which is a great thing. For the sake of consistency, certainty, and continuity, we will still begin the 20-21 school year remotely. We will continue to monitor all relevant data points related to public health and make decisions with our students' and staff's well-being in mind.

Carol Firman Stevenson (LHS '55) was one of those pioneering women that made a huge impact on the lives of many. There were no girls varsity sports at LHS or just about anywhere else in 1955, but after graduating from BGSU, she crafted a long and highly successful career as a Division 1 Track and Cross Country Coach. Carol passed away last month (see obituary below). Here's to another amazing Lakewood High School Graduate. RIP, Coach Stevenson.

post_text: A great little story about a trailblazing Ranger!
shared_text:
Charles Greanoff
July 22 at 7:44 AM ¬∑

Kathy Nortz* was a pioneer for Women's Sports. In 1977, her Freshman year, Girls Cross Country was not a sanctioned sport by the OHSAA, so she trained and ran with the boys. At invitational meets, Coach Nixon would enter her in the open race so she could compete in an official race. The following year, Lakewood High School instituted a girls cross country team. Kathy was a role model in the fledgling program and helped set the standard for its continued success. She was team captain, and LHS Most Valuable Runner.

Her coaching record in over 25 years at CWRU is outstanding. The Spartan Cross Country Team has been represented at the NCAA championships every year since 2006, including 6th place finish in the Nation, the highest national finish for any CWRU team in school history. She has coached 9 all All-Americans including one national champion in the 10,000 meters. *Now Lanese

From Superintendent Barnes:

Thank you for your patience as we worked hard over these past couple of months developing a plan that would allow us to resume our teaching and learning in a safe manner for the 2020-2021 school year in light of the coronavirus pandemic. Please take some time to view the video message presentation of our Reopening Plan. We also ask parents/guardians to complete our survey found on our website's Reopening Plan page (https://tinyurl.com/ycvqyr2d) as well so that we may know your intentions regarding returning your student(s) to school.

The Reopening Plan page will house pertinent information and be a resource throughout the school year. The page includes the Reopening Plan, the parent survey, a feedback form, frequently asked questions, and helpful resources.

We know that the uncertainty of our current times has caused much anxiety for so many. We hope that this plan helps address some of the unknowns and brings some relief in knowing our steps moving forward.

Thank you and stay safe!

The Reopening Plan page will house pertinent information and be a resource throughout the school year. The page includes the Reopening Plan, the parent survey, a feedback form, frequently asked questions, and helpful resources.

We know that the uncertainty of our current times has caused much anxiety for so many. We hope that this plan helps address some of the unknowns and brings some relief in knowing our steps moving forward.

Thank you and stay safe!

https://youtu.be/2MuUt418ws0

Lakewood Rangers Education Foundation
July 7 at 1:13 PM ¬∑

LREF will be sharing periodic profiles of some of our alumni to showcase the many interesting and impactful people who call themselves Rangers! Today we are introducing you to Donald Dahlburg. Today's profile written by LHS student journalists!

By Ayden Wacker
Class of 2021

‚ÄúHome" is a powerful and recurring theme in the life of Lakewood High alumnus, Donald Russell ‚ÄúRuss‚Äù Dahlburg. Russ was born, in fact, at home in Pittsburgh, PA in 1918 to parents of English and Swedish descent. His parents decided to move to Lakewood in 1924 when Russ was going into the first grade.

Russ moved around a lot in Lakewood and lived on Woodward, Lake and Summit avenues. Russ attended Hayes and Lincoln‚Ä¶

July 1 at 11:27 AM ¬∑

The following is a message from Stephanie Boyd about her father, Dr. Boyd's memorial service.

Details for my father's service have been finalized. The kind folks at Beck Center For the Arts in Lakewood have agreed to allow us to hold his service in their main auditorium, despite being closed due to the pandemic. This allows for plenty of space for people to be seated at safe distances from each other.

17801 Detroit Avenue

July 25, 2020

Service starts at 1PM

In lieu of flowers, please consider making a donation to the Beck Center or to the arts/music venue of your choice.

post_text: Congratulations, Patrick!
shared_text:
Lakewood Rangers Education Foundation
July 1 at 1:22 PM ¬∑

Today we have the honor to introduce you to Patrick McCallum!

Patrick had always enjoyed art class in elementary and middle school. So freshman year he signed up for an art class as he says, "I wanted a period every day where there were no questions to answer. I wanted time to let my imagination run wild and have time to create." That first high school art class fulfilled his goal and more. It nurtured a love for art that grew over the next four years, until Patrick could envision a future in art.

He is an award winning artist, having earned two Silver Keys and one Gold Key in the Scholastic Art and Writing Exhibition. One of those awards was for an imaginative Illustration created in Prisma‚Ä¶

shared_text:
Lakewood Rangers Education Foundation
June 18 at 2:10 PM ¬∑

All of these kids have been amazing, haven't they? Well, we are not about to slow down now! Today you have the pleasure of meeting Halle Sullenberger!

Halle has been very involved in her time at LHS. She ran track and field for two years, 4 years of Barnstormers, 4 years of marching band including two years as captain, St. Mark youth group, Key club, and National Honor Society.

In addition to these activities and maintaing a high GPA, Halle spends a lot of time volunteering for her community. Volunteering for fish fry's and community meals, and the community favorite Kiwanis Pizza Bake-Off!

Jani Cap, St. Mark Parish Chair, Parish Pastoral Council Youth Group Adult Leader says this of Halle‚Ä¶

Dear alumni - With reunions canceled this year due to the COVID-19 pandemic, we know you will be missing your classmates, the memories, and the fun, and we are so disappointed to not be able to welcome you into the school to show you how current students lives are still so similar, and yet so different from your own experience here at LHS!

Even though we cannot gather in person, it might lift your spirits to at least sport some new alumni gear! Click on the link below and then scroll to the bottom of the page under "new products" to find alumni shirts! Order some today and wear it in honor of your reunion! In the meantime, we can't wait to welcome you all here next summer to celebrate belatedly!

Our next outstanding student began her high school career with LHS midway through her junior year. Please say hello to Johana Guci!

Johana and her family moved to Lakewood from Albania after their Visa was approved and they moved here to join her grandparents. As frustrating and uncomfortable as it was to jump into high school midway through the school year, Johana persisted and found her place among the LHS family.

She began by signing up for H2O - to add, in her words "color" to her days, to meet good people and to learn more about her new community. This led to signing up for French Club, and then participating in the Dual Enrollment program over the summer allowed her to advance in‚Ä¶

West Shore Career-Tech
May 22 at 12:43 PM ¬∑

Please help us congratulate West Shore Career-Tech's overall Outstanding Student of the Year, Spencer Werner. Spencer is a 2020 LHS graduate and completed both the Auto Technology and Pre-Engineering (Project Lead the Way) programs. He fully embraced the opportunities provided to him through career-tech as a state qualifier in the Skills USA auto competition and placed 3rd in the Cleveland Auto Show Competition. Spencer received multiple scholarships through his competition results and was recently inducted into the National Technical Honor Society. He plans to enter the skilled trades while continuing his education in the trades.

post_text:
It‚Äôs Official!

Today at 2:00 pm, the Cuyahoga County Board of
Elections officially certified the results for Issue 28:

For the Tax Levy . . . . . . . . 7,179
Against the Tax Levy. . . . . . . 2,188

This includes all mail-in ballots and shows that nearly 77 percent of Lakewood residents who voted in this election chose to support our schools! The final number of 9,367 voters falls 391 votes short of the turnout for the 2012 primary. Considering the unprecedented circumstances that surrounded this election, that turnout is extraordinary. Thank you, Lakewood voters!

#InThisTogetherLKWD #OneHeartbeatOneLKWD

To celebrate our amazing community The North Coast College is launching the Lakewood is our Home Scholarship exclusively to Lakewood residents. These scholarships provide Lakewood residents academic scholarship covering 50% of tuition for degree-seeking students. We are excited to give our community the opportunity to earn degrees in art and design fields while staying close to home. Lakewood is our campus, and we want to be Lakewood‚Äôs first choice for art and design education. Please contact us for details about the Lakewood is our Home Scholarship Program.

Lakewood is Our Home.

Academic and residency requirements apply.

The sign up to register for a time slot for the Lakewood High's single-family Commencement is now available. Please use this link to sign up for your graduate's time. Please keep in mind that to comply with the Department of Health's approval the following safety precautions must be adhered to:

1. Attendance is limited to the graduate and four additional guests only. All students must have a preregistered time slot.

2. All individuals attending must wear masks upon entering the Civic Auditorium. The graduate may remove their mask as they walk across the stage.

3. After receiving the diploma the graduate will exit the side door of the Civic for a photo. We ask that all members then return to their vehicles promptly to allow for the next graduate to move through the procession.

4. Families that walk to the Civic Auditorium should remain outside until escorted into the Civic by a staff member.

post_text: Please consider a donation to this organization that provides so much for our Lakewood students!
shared_text:
Lakewood Rangers Education Foundation
May 5 at 12:30 PM ¬∑

We realize there is so much need in the world right now. However, if you are in a position to support a cause at this moment, it can't get any closer or more meaningful than our Lakewood students. All gifts to the Lakewood Rangers Education Foundation go directly into programs that enrich education and provide opportunities for our kids. We may not be in school at present and our fundraisers are cancelled till 2021, but the work of the Lakewood Rangers Education Foundation continues with scholarships for graduating seniors, music lessons, instruments, teaching grants for fall, etc. All gifts are 100% tax deductible. post_text: Drive-through food pantry open this Saturday for those in need!
shared_text:
Lakewood Ohio Division of Aging
April 29 at 2:46 PM ¬∑

Three Northeast Ohioans came together to start a drive-thru food pantry to help community members impacted by the coronavirus outbreak.

The pantry, called ‚ÄúFood For Families,‚Äù was created by Jane Vitou, Ellen Minerd and Eileen McGunagle.

The woman coordinated with St. Christopher Church in Rocky River to put on Saturday morning‚Äôs distribution event.

Food For Families founders started a GoFundMe account hoping to raise $5,000 to fund the pantry; they received nearly $12,000 in donations online alone. They also received donation matches from community partners.

Click here to donate to the GoFundMe account.

Officials on site told FOX 8‚Äôs Alex Stokes they raised more than $17,000 in total and were able to donate over 1,000 bags on non-perishable food items to families in need.

Food For Families will be holding another drive-thru pantry at St. Christopher‚Äôs next Saturday, May 2 from 10 a.m. to 12 p.m. Anyone in need of food is welcome to attend.

The church is located at 20141 Detroit Road. Attendees are asked to enter on Detroit Road and exit the church on Northview Road.

post_text:
Today, LHS Principal Mark Walter and teacher Ken Kozar delivered 45 face shields, created with materials and 3-D printers from the LHS Ranger Hub, to the Lakewood Fire Department. Mr. Kozar printed the face shield head bands, which took nearly 3 hours each, at home. The shields came from a partnership with Willoughby-Eastlake School of Innovation, which laser cut the plastic and donated additional shields. The Lakewood Polive Department will use them as well.

From Mr. Kozar: "During these challenging times, it's crucial to support those in our community. As efforts to contain the spread of COVID-19 continue and with the critical shortage of PPE, I'm glad I was able to do a little something to help our first responders here in Lakewood. If we're going to get through this time, we're going to have to be in this together!"

We are grateful to the Lakewood Rangers Education Foundation for providing the funding that launched the Ranger Hub several years ago. Who could have imagined the impact it would someday have for the heroes of our community!
#OneHeartbeatOneLKWD
#InThisTogetherLKWD

post_text:
TWO WEEKS UNTIL THE APRIL 28 VOTING DEADLINE!

1. How do I vote by mail?

1. Call the Cuyahoga County Board of Elections (216-443-8683) to request a Vote-by-Mail Application be mailed to your home

OR

Click the link below to access a Vote-By-Mail Application and print it out. Click ‚ÄòMarch 17, 2020 - Extended‚Äô when prompted to select an election. Fill out the application completely. Please note that voters must select one of the following types of ballots when asked on the application: Democratic, Republican, Other, or Nonpartisan/Issues Only.

2. Complete the application and mail it to: Board of Elections PO Box 89448 Cleveland, OH 44101-6448

3. Once the Cuyahoga County Board of Elections receives your application, they will mail you a ballot. Check your mailbox!

4. When you receive your ballot, please fill it out completely, and mail it back in the enclosed envelope. Your ballot must be postmarked by April 27.

5. You can check the status of your ballot here: https://boe.cuyahogacounty.us/en-US/track-my-ballot.aspx

shared_text:
Charles Greanoff
March 24 at 2:29 PM ¬∑

To all parents, students and Lakewood citizens. Over the past week, teachers have been communicating/collaborating on how to best navigate through these challenging times. I have been coached and encouraged by my colleagues‚ÄîI'm not the best with tech- in the LHS Social Studies department and elsewhere, for which I am very grateful. We are committed to providing our students with the best possible education while understanding that student circumstances vary greatly. I believe that students, teachers and parents will rise to the occasion‚Äîwe will show concern for and patience with each other.

The virus can kill or harm anyone, but the elderly and those with immunity issues are most at risk. As such, our students, especially high school seniors, are sacrificing for their elders, the persons who built our schools and society, and some of the most vulnerable. The grand lesson‚Äîone that I know our students will understand and embrace‚Äîis that we are all in this together, and we all have an important position on this team. Long Live Lakewood

Well said, as always, Dr. G!

Catching up on some good news from before the closure. This from Mrs. Masgras at Grant:
Congratulations to some amazing Pi Masters! Grant third grader Jonah M, fourth grader Delia J, and Grant alum Maya T all went to Gray House Pies in Westlake on March 14 to compete in their annual Pi Day competition. Jonah took home the first place prize of Free Pies for the year (1 pie per month). He recited 314 digits of pi from memory (in honor of 3/14 - Pi Day.). The second place finisher had 255 and third 170. Delia and Maya were both top finishers taking home a pie of their choice and Pi Master t Shirts for their efforts! What a Pi-normous feat by all of these students.

post_text: For those students in our AP classes:
shared_text:
The College Board
March 16 at 2:26 PM ¬∑

The College Board is developing tools to mitigate the impact of school closures on students in the Advanced Placement Program. All AP students and teachers will be able to draw on the free online resources that were provided to every AP classroom this fall. Additional resources will be made easily accessible to AP students and teachers through mobile phones and other devices. These include free online AP lessons and review sessions from some of the top AP teachers in the country.

The AP program is finalizing streamlined AP exam options that would allow students to test at home, depending on the situation in May. We‚Äôre working to give every AP student the opportunity to claim the credit they‚Äôve earned. The AP Program will communicate the details of these additional solutions to educators and students by March 20.

The College Board‚Äôs focus will remain on student safety and ensuring all students have the tools they need to work, and opportunities to receive the credit they have earned, during this challenging time.

More details: http://spr.ly/61861srPq.

A message from Mr. DiMascio regarding those applying for West Shore next year...

This message is for families that have applied for programs AND currently enrolled students:

Due to the COVID-19 outbreak and extended closure, we have postponed our announcement about accepted applicants. We are working diligently to inform you of acceptance over the next two weeks. Thank you for your understanding.

If anyone has any questions/concerns during the extended closure--we are all still working and available. The preferred method for contact is now email. If you have questions that relate to your child's teacher, reach out to them.
